Welcome to this lecture where we are going to understand what is Amazon VPC.In AWS world, VPC stands for virtual private cloud.So, you can think of VPC as your own private data center inside the AWS cloud.And why do we need this?Because when you are deploying your application inside the AWS cloud, you need to create an isolatednetwork environment for your applications so that they can be safe from the other AWS accounts or fromthe external world.So, VPC provides you with network isolation.That basically means that you can launch your AWS resources, like your EC2 instances, your RDS databases,lambda functions, or other resources. inside this isolated private network.And since it's private, external world cannot access your application by default.So in short, VPC is a logically isolated section of the AWS cloud where you can launch AWS resourcesin a virtual network that you define.And that virtual network closely resembles a traditional network that you might operate in your own data center.You can configure your own networking components like subnets, route tables, internet gateways, networkgateways, security groups, etc. with VPC.And I mentioned that VPC is private by default, but that doesn't mean that you cannot make them public.You can still make your resources public if you want them to receive traffic from the internet, for example,a web server where youcyber have to interact with the web browsers online.And I should also mention that VPC is logically distributed across a region.So, you can think of it is geographically isolated in specific AWS region, but logically isolated acrossall availability zones within that region.And what does that mean?So basically, when you create a VPC, you can use differentsubnets, but those subnets can be placed in different availability zones within the same region.And that helps you to provide high availability to your application because you can place your resources in multiple AZs within the same VPC.This is what makes your architecture truly fault tolerant and resilient and those resources can talk to each other.For example, you can have an EC2 instance in one availability zone and it can reachout to your RDS database which is in another availability zone in the same VPC.Now, what is the other important thing about VPC?VPC allows you to have complete control over the virtual networking environment.To decide what IP address range to use, what subnets touse, what security groups to use, and so on.This gives you granular control on your entire infrastructure down to the port level even.You can configure port level security rules for your applications.And not only that, VPC also allows you to connect your on-premises resources with the cloud private ly using technologies like AWS Direct Connect ordevices like customer gateway.By using these you can build hybrid cloud architecture.And if you are thinking that VPC can be created on a per-account basis only, then yes, you are right.VPC is limited to a single AWS account.So even if you have multiple AWS accounts, you still have to create separate VPC for each AWS account.And by the way, the VPC has a default maximum limit of 5 VPCs per region per account, but that can be increased by contacting AWS support.Now let's also talk about the VPC and its life cycle.One thing that you should understand that VPC is a regional service, so it is tied to AWS region.And since VPC is tied to region, the resources that you launch inside VPC will have scope limited tothe region only.But let me just remind you that not all AWS services are regional services.Some AWS services are global, like IAM or route 53 or CloudFront.Some services are zonal or AZ specific, and some services are regional.Before I end this lecture, I should also mention that the VPC can be scaled up and down as per your need.But for that you have to use the VPC wizard or manually create VPC components.And you have to understand that VPC can be either created using VPC wizard, which is managed VPCworkflow, or you can create VPC manually from scratch.And another thing that you should know about VPC that the default VPC is very important concept.Every AWS account comes with a default VPC in every region.And what that means is if you don't explicitly create your own VPC, your applications launch into that default VPC by default.And why is the default VPC important?Because it is pre-configured with all the networking components required to run your applications out of the box. And it also has aninternet gateway for fast connectivity to internet.And since it has Internet Gateway attached, it can provide internet connectivity out of the box.But obviously, this default VPC is not recommended for production workloads.But for learning purposes or for labs, it's absolutely fine.And you can also create custom VPC to better suit your needs.Now, before I end this lecture, just one more thing.Every VPC has a network boundary isolation, which means the traffic between VPCs even in the samesame account or different account is not allowed by default.And now of course that can be changed using the peering and transit gateway and we will see that in theadvanced sections of this course.Okay, so that's all about what is VPC.Let's summarize everything that we talked about.VPC is a virtual private cloud that gives you network isolation for your applications.VPC contains AWS resources like EC2, RDS, etc.VPC is logically isolated but distributed across multiple availability zones in the same region.VPC is a regional service and gives you complete control over virtual networking environment.VPC can be created per account basis and by default every account has default VPC with Internetgateway.And network boundary isolation is maintained between VPCs.Okay, I think that's everything. ``` 

