## Section 17: CloudFront Overview (KK-CS45-script-v2)

### Overview
Section 17 encompasses CloudFront (AWS's Content Delivery Network), Global Accelerator, and associated advanced networking services. This section covers CloudFront origins, security, encryption, geographic restrictions, edge functions (CloudFront Functions and Lambda@Edge), and Global Accelerator for TCP/UDP traffic optimization. Key concepts include content caching, origin protection, global distribution, and edge computing capabilities.

### Key Concepts/Deep Dive

#### CloudFront Architecture Overview
CloudFront serves as AWS's global CDN with 225+ points of presence (215+ edge locations, 13 regional edge caches). It provides performance acceleration through edge caching while adding security layers against DDoS attacks and integrating with Shield, WAF, and Route 53.

**Cache Hierarchy Flow**:
- Edge Locations: Primary caching layer closest to users
- Regional Edge Caches: Larger capacity caches serving multiple edge locations
- Origins: S3 buckets, ALBs, NLBs, EC2 instances, or custom HTTP endpoints

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Viewer Request] --> B[Edge Location]
    B --> C{Cached Content?}
    C -->|No| D[Regional Edge Cache]
    D --> E{Cached Content?}
    E -->|No| F[Origin Fetch]
    F --> G[Content → Regional Cache → Edge Location → User]
```

#### CloudFront Origins and Groups
**Origin Types**:
- **S3 Bucket**: Static content with Origin Access Control (OAC) for security
- **VPC Origins**: Private ALBs, NLBs, EC2 in private subnets (most secure)
- **Custom Origins**: Public HTTP endpoints with IP whitelisting
- **MediaStore/MediaPackage**: Video streaming content

**Origin Groups**: Enable high availability through failover
- Primary origin + secondary origin
- Automatic failover on status codes (500, 502, 503, 504)
- S3 cross-region replication for seamless redundancy

#### CloudFront Security Framework
**Origin Access Control (OAC)**:
- Restricts S3 bucket access to CloudFront only
- Eliminates direct S3 URL exposure
- Bucket policy denies all access except from CloudFront OAC

**VPC Origins**: 
- Origins in private subnets
- No internet exposure required
- Optimal security configuration

**Custom Origin Protection**:
- Header-based authentication
- IP-based whitelisting using CloudFront ranges (`https://ip-ranges.amazonaws.com/ip-ranges.json`)
- WAF integration for enhanced filtering

#### CloudFront HTTPS and End-to-End Encryption
**Certificate Management**:
- Default: `*.cloudfront.net` (free, automatic)
- Custom: ACM certificates in us-east-1 region
- Third-party certificates uploaded to ACM/IAM

**Viewer Protocol Policies**:
- HTTP and HTTPS (allows both)
- Redirect HTTP to HTTPS (security recommended)
- HTTPS Only (maximum security)

**Origin Protocol Policies**:
- HTTP/HTTPS/Match Viewer
- HTTPS Only for end-to-end encryption

**Field-Level Encryption**:
- Encrypts sensitive request fields (PCI/HIPAA compliance)
- Public key encryption at CloudFront
- Private key decryption at origin
- Note: Deprecated but exam-relevant

#### Geographic Restrictions
**Configuration Options**:
- Whitelist: Only specified countries allowed
- Blacklist: Specified countries blocked
- Distribution-level or behavior-level restrictions

**Implementation**:
- Uses MaxMind GeoIP databases
- IPv4/IPv6 support
- Violation responses: 403 Forbidden

#### CloudFront Functions vs Lambda@Edge

| Feature | CloudFront Functions | Lambda@Edge |
|---------|----------------------|-------------|
| Runtime | JavaScript only | Node.js, Python, Go |
| Execution Location | Edge Locations | Regional Edge Caches |
| Max Execution Time | <1 second | 5-30 seconds |
| Memory | 2 MB | 128 MB - 10 GB |
| Isolation | Process-based | VM-based |
| Triggers | Viewer Request/Response | All events |
| Network Access | No | Yes |
| Free Tier | Yes | No |
| Cost per 1M Requests | ~$0.10 | ~$0.60 |

**Use Cases**:
- CloudFront Functions: Cache key manipulation, header transformations, basic auth
- Lambda@Edge: Third-party API calls, content personalization, image optimization

#### AWS Global Accelerator
**Architecture**:
- Anycast IPv4 addresses routing to nearest AWS edge
- Optimized TCP connection establishment
- Automatic failover and health checks

**Key Differences from CloudFront**:
- Transport layer (TCP/UDP) vs Application layer (HTTP)
- No caching capabilities
- Deterministic routing to specific instances

### Hands-On Demonstrations
Practical sections covered:
- Origin Groups: S3 cross-region replication failover
- ALB Security: Custom headers and listener rules restricting ALB access to CloudFront
- CloudFront Functions: JavaScript edge functions for request/response manipulation
- Global Accelerator: Multi-region application acceleration with health checks

### Expert Insight
**Real-world Applications**:
- E-commerce: CloudFront for static assets, Global Accelerator for checkout APIs
- Media streaming: MediaStore with CloudFront for global video delivery
- Global SaaS: Lambda@Edge for compliance and regional personalization

**Expert Path Recommendations**:
- Master cache behavior optimization and invalidation strategies
- Implement comprehensive CloudWatch monitoring
- Understand trade-offs between CloudFront Functions and Lambda@Edge
- Design for global failover scenarios with origin groups

**Common Pitfalls**:
- Exposing origins directly without security restrictions
- Choosing Lambda@Edge for simple tasks (higher cost)
- Ignoring GeoIP database limitations (VPN circumvention)
- Not testing failover configurations

**Advanced Concepts**:
- Custom error pages for geo-restrictions
- Request collapsing to reduce origin load
- Signed URLs and cookies for content protection
- Real-time logs for debugging edge function issues

</details>
